Of the value of the latter I have already adduced a striking instance. Of the former I will only say that, irrespective of the erudition Which is so eminently displayed in the preface and noteS, I have in numerous cases derived assistance and information from a glance at the lucid and comprehensive Indeoe Rerum, Which I could only have obtained otherwise by a toilsome search through many volumeS.

It will be observed that I have invariably spelt the name of my author Symeon, instead of Simeon, the orthography adopted by Twysden on the authority of the Cambridge MS. In this I am supported by the list of monks in the autograph copy of the History of the Church of Durham, and by the spelling of the name in the Liber Vitae, and the ancient Obituary of that church. The same orthography also prevails in Reginald’s Miracles of St. Cuthbert, and in the Cotton MS. of the Arch- bishops of York, and is adopted by Leland.

I. H. H.
